<p>I used Homebrew to install nano by issuing the command (brew install nano) so that I can have the latest nano version (after tapping the home-brew/dupes). The problem is that I have a version of nano with more that the half compiler options missing. Here is the result of giving nano -V to the terminal :</p>  <blockquote>   <p>GNU nano, version 2.4.2  (C) 1999..2015 Free Software Foundation, Inc.   Email: nano@nano-editor.org   Web: <a href="http://www.nano-editor.org/" rel="nofollow">http://www.nano-editor.org/</a>  Compiled   options: --disable-libmagic --disable-nls --enable-utf8</p> </blockquote>  <p>and here is the result of the same command but using the default el capitan nano version /usr/bin/nano -V to the terminal :</p>  <blockquote>   <p>GNU nano version 2.0.6 (compiled 15:38:45, Aug 22 2015)  Email:   nano@nano-editor.org  Web: <a href="http://www.nano-editor.org/" rel="nofollow">http://www.nano-editor.org/</a>  Compiled   options: --disable-nls --enable-color --enable-extra   --enable-multibuffer --enable-nanorc --enable-utf8</p> </blockquote>  <p>Now looking at the homebrew formula I see that homebrew tries to install all the flags but for some reason the final result contains only some of them.</p>  <p>Any ideas? Thank you.</p>